Credit Card Fraud Detection using Machine Learning

Credit Card Transaction Dataset

Project Overview

Credit card fraud poses a significant challenge to financial institutions and consumers, with billions in losses annually. Machine learning can help identify fraudulent transactions while minimizing false alerts that impact legitimate customers.

This project utilizes an anonymized credit card transactions dataset to build a classification model that identifies fraudulent transactions based on 28 PCA-transformed features, along with time and amount data.

Data source: Kaggle dataset derived from European cardholders' transactions in September 2013 (collaboration between Worldline and the Machine Learning Group of ULB).

Dataset Information

  • Source: European credit card transactions
  • # Instances: 284,807
  • # Features: 30 (28 PCA-transformed + Time + Amount)
  • Target Variable:
    • 1 (Fraudulent Transaction)
    • 0 (Legitimate Transaction)
  • Class Imbalance: 492 frauds (0.172%) of all transactions

Project Goals

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

    • Analyze class imbalance
    • Understand feature distributions
    • Examine temporal patterns in fraud
    • Visualize feature relationships

  2. Preprocessing & Model Development

    • Handle severe class imbalance
    • Scale features appropriately
    • Implement train/validation/test split
    • Apply cross-validation

  3. Model Building & Evaluation

    • Train multiple classifiers: Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and XGBoost
    • Evaluate using AUPRC, ROC-AUC, and F1-score
    • Focus on practical metrics: detection rate and false alert rate

  4. Feature Importance & Business Impact

    • Identify key fraud indicators
    • Balance detection rate vs. operational efficiency
    • Provide actionable business recommendations

Technologies Used

  • Programming Language: Python
  • Libraries: Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib, Seaborn, Scikit-Learn, XGBoost, imbalanced-learn

Expected Outcomes

This project aims to develop a practical fraud detection system that balances high fraud detection rates with manageable false alerts. The focus is on creating an operationally viable solution that can be implemented in real-world financial systems.

Exploratory Data Analysis - Credit Card Fraud

Data Imbalance

  • Total transactions: 284,807
  • Fraudulent: 492 (0.172%)
  • Legitimate: 284,315 (99.828%)

Feature Distribution Analysis

PCA Components (V1-V28)

  1. Individual Feature Analysis:

    • Most features centered at zero (PCA-transformed)
    • Notable outliers in V14, V12, V10
    • V4, V11, V19 show normal distribution patterns

  2. Fraud vs Legitimate Distribution:

    • Strong separation in V4, V11, V14 (distinct peaks for fraud)
    • V24 shows complex multimodal distribution
    • V25, V26 demonstrate similar patterns between classes
    • V1-V3 show clear shifts in distribution between fraud/normal cases

Amount Distribution

  • Highly right-skewed (log scale used)
  • Most transactions under 5000
  • Several outliers above 20,000

Key Insights

  1. Severe class imbalance requires careful model selection/evaluation
  2. Several PCA components show good discriminative power for fraud detection
  3. Feature engineering might focus on V4, V11, V14 given their separation patterns

Baseline Model Selection

Preprocessing

  1. Train/Val/Test Split: 60/20/20
  2. Feature scaling with StandardScaler
  3. SMOTE on training data only
  4. 5-fold CV for model validation

Model Choices

  1. Logistic Regression
  • Simple, interpretable baseline
  • class_weight='balanced' for imbalance
  1. Random Forest
  • Handles nonlinear relationships
  • class_weight='balanced'
  • n_jobs=-1 for parallel processing
  1. XGBoost
  • Strong with imbalanced data
  • scale_pos_weight for class balance

# Split features and target
X = df.drop('Class', axis=1)
y = df['Class']

# Train-test split with stratification
X_train_full, X_test, y_train_full, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42)
X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X_train_full, y_train_full, test_size=0.25, stratify=y_train_full, random_state=42)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_val_scaled = scaler.transform(X_val)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

# SMOTE only on training data
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced = smote.fit_resample(X_train_scaled, y_train)
In[13]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.metrics import average_precision_score, roc_auc_score
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import xgboost as xgb

# Base models with CV
models = {
   'logistic': LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced'),
   'rf': RandomForestClassifier(class_weight='balanced', n_jobs=-1),
   'xgb': xgb.XGBClassifier(scale_pos_weight=len(y_train_balanced[y_train_balanced==0])/len(y_train_balanced[y_train_balanced==1]))
}

# CV scores
for name, model in models.items():
   cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced, cv=5, scoring='average_precision')
   print(f"{name} CV AUPRC: {cv_scores.mean():.3f} (+/- {cv_scores.std()*2:.3f})")
   
   # Fit on full training data
   model.fit(X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced)
   
   # Validation scores
   val_pred = model.predict_proba(X_val_scaled)[:, 1]
   print(f"{name} Validation AUPRC: {average_precision_score(y_val, val_pred):.3f}")
   print(f"{name} Validation ROC-AUC: {roc_auc_score(y_val, val_pred):.3f}\n")

# import confusion matrix
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Plot Confusion Matrices
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))

for idx, (name, model) in enumerate(models.items()):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_val_scaled)
    conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_val, y_pred)
    
    sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", 
                xticklabels=["Normal", "Fraud"], 
                yticklabels=["Normal", "Fraud"], 
                ax=axes[idx])
    axes[idx].set_title(f"{name}")
    axes[idx].set_xlabel("Predicted")
    axes[idx].set_ylabel("Actual")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Fraud-specific metrics
for name, model in models.items():
    y_pred = model.predict(X_val_scaled)
    conf_mat = confusion_matrix(y_val, y_pred)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = conf_mat.ravel()
    
    print(f"\n{name}:")
    print(f"Missed Frauds (FN): {fn}")
    print(f"False Alerts (FP): {fp}")
    print(f"Detection Rate: {tp/(tp+fn):.2%}")
    print(f"False Alert Rate: {fp/(fp+tn):.2%}")

Model Evaluation & Results

Performance Metrics Summary

Model Detection Rate False Alert Rate F1 Score AUPRC ROC AUC
Logistic Regression 86.87% 2.57% 0.105 0.674 0.972
Random Forest 77.78% 0.01% 0.842 0.804 0.961
XGBoost 78.79% 0.04% 0.788 0.806 0.967

Critical Error Analysis

  1. False Negatives (Missed Frauds)

    • Logistic: 13 missed (lowest) but misleading given high false alerts
    • RF/XGB: ~21-22 missed, more balanced with false alert rate

  2. False Positives (False Alerts)

    • RF: Exceptional precision (7 false alerts)
    • XGB: Balanced (21 false alerts)
    • Logistic: Poor precision (1,460 false alerts)

Model Comparison

  1. Random Forest Performance

    • Highest F1 score (0.842)
    • Minimal false alerts (7)
    • Trade-off: Slightly more missed frauds

  2. Model Trade-offs

    • RF: Best balance (F1=0.842, minimal false alerts)
    • XGB: Close second (F1=0.788, balanced errors)
    • Logistic: High detection but impractical false alert rate

Business Recommendations

  • RF recommended for production: best F1 score, minimal investigation burden
  • Consider XGB if investigation resources allow for more false alerts
  • Logistic impractical despite high detection rate

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Store best parameters during grid search
best_params = {}
best_scores = {}

# RF parameters
rf_params = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200],
    'max_depth': [10, 20, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5],
    'class_weight': ['balanced']
}

# XGB parameters
xgb_params = {
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1],
    'n_estimators': [100, 200],
    'scale_pos_weight': [len(y_train[y_train==0])/len(y_train[y_train==1])]
}

# Grid search and store results
for name, (model, params) in {'rf': (RandomForestClassifier(), rf_params), 
                             'xgb': (xgb.XGBClassifier(), xgb_params)}.items():
    grid = GridSearchCV(model, params, scoring='average_precision', cv=5)
    grid.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    best_params[name] = grid.best_params_
    best_scores[name] = grid.best_score_
    print(f"\n{name} Best params:", grid.best_params_)
    print(f"Best AUPRC: {grid.best_score_:.3f}")

# Create and evaluate tuned models
models_tuned = {
    'RF (tuned)': RandomForestClassifier(**best_params['rf']),
    'XGB (tuned)': xgb.XGBClassifier(**best_params['xgb'])
}

rf Best params: {'class_weight': 'balanced', 'max_depth': None, 'min_samples_split': 2, 'n_estimators': 200}
Best AUPRC: 0.849

xgb Best params: {'learning_rate': 0.1, 'max_depth': 7, 'n_estimators': 200, 'scale_pos_weight': 578.264406779661}

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve, roc_curve

# Create ROC Curve
fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_test_pred_proba)
# Create PR Curve
precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_test_pred_proba)

# Plot both curves
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))

# ROC Curve
ax1.plot(fpr, tpr)
ax1.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')  # diagonal line
ax1.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')
ax1.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')
ax1.set_title(f'ROC Curve (AUC = {test_roc_auc:.3f})')

# PR Curve
ax2.plot(recall, precision)
ax2.set_xlabel('Recall')
ax2.set_ylabel('Precision')
ax2.set_title(f'Precision-Recall Curve (AUC = {test_auprc:.3f})')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Conclusion

Project Summary

This project developed a credit card fraud detection system using machine learning, addressing a significant class imbalance (0.172% fraud cases). Through systematic evaluation of multiple models and careful tuning, we achieved a robust fraud detection solution.

Key Achievements

  1. Model Performance

    • 82.65% fraud detection rate
    • Only 0.02% false alert rate
    • Strong AUPRC (0.873) and ROC-AUC (0.978)

  2. Operational Efficiency

    • 81 out of 98 frauds detected
    • Only 12 false alerts per 57,000 transactions
    • Clear feature importance hierarchy for investigation

  3. Business Value

    • Manageable investigation workload
    • Data-driven fraud detection process
    • Balance between detection and operational efficiency

Limitations and Future Work

  1. Model Limitations

    • 17 undetected frauds require pattern analysis
    • Heavy reliance on V14 feature
    • PCA transformation limits feature interpretability

  2. Future Improvements

    • Explore deep learning approaches
    • Investigate temporal patterns in missed frauds
    • Develop ensemble methods for robust detection
    • Consider cost-sensitive learning based on transaction amounts

Final Thoughts

The developed solution provides a practical balance between fraud detection and operational efficiency. While not perfect, it offers a solid foundation for protecting against credit card fraud while maintaining manageable false alert rates.
